\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Camera Concepts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geometric characteristics of a camera obscura (aka 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pinhole camera
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

central perspective projection camera
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) are concerned with the location of the light admitting aperture relative
 to the plane on which the image is formed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a typical modern camera, the image plane is the surface of a light sensitive
 semi-conductor devics (generally a CMOS or CCD).
 The detector cells (aka 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pixels
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) on the device form a natural coordinate system, in terms of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

row
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

column
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

