\begin_layout Subsubsection
Entrance Angle Magnitude
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introduce vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, to represent the object point separation via definition,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\equiv x_{2}-x_{1}
\]

\end_inset

and square each side of this relationship to obtain,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d^{2}=x_{2}^{2}-2x_{2}\cdot x_{1}+x_{1}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simultaneously, the entry angle magnitude, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, satisfies the Ref space triangle law of cosines relationship, via
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d^{2}=\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}-2\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}\cos\alpha
\]

\end_inset

which may also be expressed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\cos\alpha=\frac{\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}-d^{2}}{2\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}}\label{eq:CosineExterior}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exit Angle Magnitude
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In similar fashion, let the relative detector point separation be represented
 by vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\equiv m_{2}-m_{1}
\]

\end_inset

and square each side to obtain,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r^{2}=m_{2}^{2}-2m_{2}\cdot m_{1}+m_{1}^{2}\label{eq:Def_rSq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exit angle magnitude, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, satisfies the corresponding vertex magnitude relationship via the law
 of cosines,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{2}=\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}-2\mu_{1}\mu_{2}\cos\beta
\]

\end_inset

or, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\cos\beta=\frac{\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}-r^{2}}{2\mu_{1}\mu_{2}}\label{eq:CosineInternal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coangularity Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ideal perspective condition may be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\alpha$
\end_inset

, which also requires that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\beta=\cos\alpha
\]

\end_inset

This equivalence may be expressed in terms of the above triangle relationships
 from equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CosineExterior"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CosineInternal"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}-d^{2}}{\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}}=\frac{\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}-r^{2}}{\mu_{1}\mu_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The left hand side, may be evaluated in terms of measured object space distances
, while evaluation of the right hand side requires knowledge of camera interior
 parameters including the principal distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For convenience of notation, introduce a new scalar parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, that is proportional to the common value in this equivalence.
 For calibration purposes, it is particularly useful to associate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 more closely with the object space quantity on the left and to 
\emph on
define
\emph default
 the parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma\equiv\frac{\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}-d^{2}}{\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}}=2\cos\beta
\]

\end_inset

This allows expressing the coangularity condition as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{1}\mu_{2}\gamma=\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}-r^{2}\label{eq:CoAngleInMu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Squared Relationships
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Square both sides of equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CoAngleInMu"

\end_inset

 to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{1}^{2}\mu_{2}^{2}\gamma^{2}=\left(\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}\right)^{2}-2\left(\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}\right)r^{2}+r^{4}\label{eq:SqSqs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since both the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}$
\end_inset

 are inherently positive, squaring these quantities does not significantly
 change the underlying relationship.
 However, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 can be either positive or negative, the squaring operation conflates two
 cases and thereby introduces a possible secondary solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I.e.
 this squared relationship, still represents the true physical configuration
 associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=2\cos\beta$
\end_inset

, but the squaring operation also introduces an artificial solution associated
 with the vertex angle supplement, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\gamma=2\cos\left(\pi-\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, any inversion process to determine, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, should be expected to require also a disambiguation consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To evaluate this relationship in terms of the (unknown) principal distance
 parameter, begin by squaring both sides of equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DetDists"

\end_inset

 to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{j}^{2} & =\left(m_{j}-h\right)^{2}\\
 & =m_{j}^{2}-\left(m_{j}h+hm_{j}\right)+h^{2}\\
 & =m_{j}^{2}-2m_{j}\cdot h+h^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The middle term on the right may be expressed in terms of relationship
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MeaProjection"

\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{j}^{2}=m_{j}^{2}-2\rho_{j}^{2}+h^{2}\label{eq:MuSquared_j}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Employ this interior distance relationship for each point to express the
 product
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{1}^{2}\mu_{2}^{2} & =\left(\left(m_{1}^{2}-2\rho_{1}^{2}\right)+h^{2}\right)\left(\left(m_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{2}^{2}\right)+h^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Check as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{j}\equiv m_{j}^{2}-2\rho_{j}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{1}\mu_{2}=\left(y_{1}+h^{2}\right)\left(y_{2}+h^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{1}\mu_{2}=y_{1}y_{2}+\left(y_{1}+y_{2}\right)h^{2}+h^{4}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{1}y_{2} & =m_{1}^{2}\left(m_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{2}^{2}\right)-2\rho_{1}^{2}\left(m_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\\
 & =m_{1}^{2}m_{2}^{2}-2m_{1}^{2}\rho_{2}^{2}+-2\rho_{1}^{2}m_{2}^{2}--2\rho_{1}^{2}2\rho_{2}^{2}\\
 & =m_{1}^{2}m_{2}^{2}-2m_{1}^{2}\rho_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{1}^{2}m_{2}^{2}+4\rho_{1}^{2}\rho_{2}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{1}+y_{2} & =m_{1}^{2}-2\rho_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{2}^{2}\\
 & =m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{1}\mu_{2} & =h^{4}\\
 & +\left(m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\right)h^{2}\\
 & +m_{1}^{2}m_{2}^{2}-2m_{1}^{2}\rho_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{1}^{2}m_{2}^{2}+4\rho_{1}^{2}\rho_{2}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Distribute the multiplications to yield
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{1}^{2}\mu_{2}^{2} & =\left(m_{1}^{2}-2\rho_{1}^{2}\right)\left(m_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{2}^{2}\right)+\left(\left(m_{1}^{2}-2\rho_{1}^{2}\right)+\left(m_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\right)h^{2}+h^{2}h^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{1}^{2}\mu_{2}^{2} & =h^{4}\\
 & +\left[m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\right]h^{2}\\
 & +\left[\left(m_{1}^{2}-2\rho_{1}^{2}\right)\left(m_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introduce intermediate scalar, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{2}$
\end_inset

, defined as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu^{2}\equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}\right)-\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\label{eq:DefNuSq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and scalar, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{4}$
\end_inset

, defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega^{4}\equiv\left(m_{1}^{2}-2\rho_{1}^{2}\right)\left(m_{2}^{2}-2\rho_{2}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
to express the product of squared interior distance values as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mu_{1}^{2}\mu_{2}^{2} & =h^{4}+2\nu^{2}h^{2}+\omega^{4}\label{eq:ProdSqMu1Mu2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the exponents included in the expression of quantities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{4}$
\end_inset

, are used primarily to track the algebraic order with which they are defined.
 In this way, equations are expressed with notation in which terms have
 homogeneous order.
 The numeric values associated to the quantities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{4}$
\end_inset

, may be negative.
 However, this is not a concern since not roots of these values are required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a next step in relating equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SqSqs"

\end_inset

 to principal distance parameters, express the sum of squared interior distance
 values by adding equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MuSquared_j"

\end_inset

 for the two cases of 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2$
\end_inset

 to yield
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}\right)=m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)+2h^{2}
\]

\end_inset

This may be expressed in terms of intermediate parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{2}$
\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}\right)=2\left(\nu^{2}+h^{2}\right)\label{eq:SumSqMu1Mu2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, square this relationship to obtain,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}\right)^{2}=4\left(\nu^{4}+2\nu^{2}h^{2}+h^{4}\right)\label{eq:SqSumSqMu1Mu2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
CHECKS:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{1}^{2}\mu_{2}^{2}\gamma^{2}=\left(\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}\right)^{2}-2\left(\mu_{1}^{2}+\mu_{2}^{2}\right)r^{2}+r^{4}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(h^{4}+2\nu^{2}h^{2}+\omega^{4}\right)\gamma^{2}=4\left(\nu^{4}+2\nu^{2}h^{2}+h^{4}\right)-2\left(2\left(\nu^{2}+h^{2}\right)\right)r^{2}+r^{4}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(h^{4}+2\nu^{2}h^{2}+\omega^{4}\right)\gamma^{2}=4\left(\nu^{4}+2\nu^{2}h^{2}+h^{4}\right)-4\left(\nu^{2}+h^{2}\right)r^{2}+r^{4}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Return to Coangularity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ProdSqMu1Mu2"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SqSumSqMu1Mu2"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SumSqMu1Mu2"

\end_inset

, to re-express relationship
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SqSqs"

\end_inset

 as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(h^{4}+2\nu^{2}h^{2}+\omega^{4}\right)\gamma^{2} & =4\left(\nu^{4}+2\nu^{2}h^{2}+h^{4}\right)\\
 & -4\left(\nu^{2}+h^{2}\right)r^{2}\\
 & +r^{4}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearrange and gather terms by order of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma^{2}h^{4}+2\nu^{2}\gamma^{2}h^{2}+\omega^{4}\gamma^{2}=4\nu^{4}+8\nu^{2}h^{2}+4h^{4}-4\nu^{2}r^{2}-4r^{2}h^{2}+r^{4}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =+4h^{4}-\gamma^{2}h^{4}\\
 & +8\nu^{2}h^{2}-2\nu^{2}\gamma^{2}h^{2}-4r^{2}h^{2}\\
 & -\omega^{4}\gamma^{2}+4\nu^{4}-4\nu^{2}r^{2}+r^{4}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\left(4-\gamma^{2}\right)h^{4}\\
 & +\left(8\nu^{2}-2\nu^{2}\gamma^{2}-4r^{2}\right)h^{2}\\
 & +\left(4\nu^{4}-4\nu^{2}r^{2}+r^{4}-\omega^{4}\gamma^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a quadratic expression in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}$
\end_inset

, for which all the coefficients are completely established in terms of
 measured values.
 I.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{a}h^{4}+2\kappa_{b}h^{2}+\kappa_{c}=0\label{eq:QuadIn_hSq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\kappa_{a} & \equiv4-\gamma^{2}\\
\kappa_{b} & \equiv4\nu^{2}-\nu^{2}\gamma^{2}-2r^{2}\\
\kappa_{c} & \equiv4\nu^{4}-4\nu^{2}r^{2}+r^{4}-\omega^{4}\gamma^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DefNuSq"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Def_rSq"

\end_inset

 may be combined to evaluate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\nu^{2}-r^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, in terms of measured values,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu^{2}-r^{2} & =m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\\
 & -\left(m_{2}^{2}-2m_{2}\cdot m_{1}+m_{1}^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu^{2}-r^{2} & =m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\\
 & -m_{2}^{2}+2m_{2}\cdot m_{1}-m_{1}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu^{2}-r^{2} & =+2m_{2}\cdot m_{1}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\\
 & +m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}-m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu^{2}-r^{2} & =2m_{2}\cdot m_{1}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu^{2}-r^{2} & =2\left(m_{2}\cdot m_{1}-\rho_{1}^{2}-\rho_{2}^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu^{2}-r^{2} & =2\left(m_{2}\cdot m_{1}-\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}^{2}$
\end_inset

 values are evaluated with equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MeaProjection"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For origin at the corner of the detector, the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 are all non-negative.
 Also, since the detector occupies a single quadrant, then 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le m_{2}\cdot m_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}=\left(m_{1r}+m_{2r}\right)\eta_{r}+\left(m_{1c}+m_{2c}\right)\eta_{c}
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}\perp m_{2}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu^{2}-r^{2}\underset{\perp}{=}-2\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}\parallel m_{2}$
\end_inset

, then, let, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}=\sigma m_{1}$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2} & \underset{\parallel}{=}\left(m_{1}+\sigma m_{1}\right)\cdot h\\
 & =\left(1+\sigma\right)m_{1}\cdot h
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu^{2}-r^{2} & \underset{\parallel}{=}2\left(\sigma m_{1}m_{1}-\left(\rho_{1}^{2}+\rho_{2}^{2}\right)\right)\\
 & =2\left(\sigma\left|m_{1}\right|^{2}-\left(1+\sigma\right)\left|m_{1}\right|\hat{m_{1}}\cdot h\right)\\
 & =2\left|m_{1}\right|\left(-\left(\hat{m_{1}}\cdot h\right)-\sigma\left(\left(\hat{m_{1}}\cdot h\right)-\left|m_{1}\right|\right)\right)\\
 & =-2\left|m_{1}\right|\left(\hat{m_{1}}\cdot h+\sigma\left(\hat{m_{1}}\cdot h-\hat{m_{1}}\cdot m_{1}\right)\right)\\
 & =-2\left|m_{1}\right|\left(\hat{m_{1}}\cdot h+\sigma\left(\hat{m_{1}}\cdot\left(h-m_{1}\right)\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Probably is generally negative.
\end_layout

